while testing #21004:

In my hello world extension I just replaced the showInformationMessage by this:
```js
        vscode.window.showWarningMessage('hello world', { modal: false },
             { title: 'hello', isCloseAffordance: true },
             { title: 'world', isCloseAffordance: true }
        );
```
This works fine and TS does not show an error.

Then I changed the first 'isCloseAffordance' to 'false:
```js
        vscode.window.showWarningMessage('hello world', { modal: false },
             { title: 'hello', isCloseAffordance: false },
             { title: 'world', isCloseAffordance: true }
        );
```

Now I get this TS error:
![2017-02-22_15-33-29](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1898161/23215894/467f16c4-f914-11e6-8155-3401b1999a58.png)

So TS can no longer infer the correct overload for showWarningMessage.
Adding an explicit generic type parameter fixes that: 
```js
        vscode.window.showWarningMessage<vscode.MessageItem>('hello world', { modal: false },
             { title: 'hello', isCloseAffordance: false },
             { title: 'world', isCloseAffordance: true }
        );
```

I would expect that TS does not complain in this case.
